					<span class="brand-name">StudyKit</span>
				</a>
				<p class="article-meta">Citation Guides · Updated for 2025</p>
				<h1>APA vs MLA Citation: Which One Should You Use?</h1>
				<p class="subtitle">
					Two style guides, two sets of rules — here is how APA and MLA differ, and how to pick the right one for your assignment.
				</p>
			</header>

			<main class="main">
				<article class="card article">
					<p>
						If you have ever stared at a syllabus wondering whether your professor wants APA or MLA, you are
						not alone. These are the two most common citation styles in American colleges and high schools,
						and they look similar enough to cause real confusion — until you lose points for using the wrong
						one. Both systems give credit to your sources and help readers find the originals, but they
						organize information differently, emphasize different details, and serve different academic fields.
					</p>
					<p>
						This guide compares APA and MLA side by side: when each style is used, how citations are formatted,
						and what your paper should look like. By the end, you will know which format your assignment
						probably requires — and how to build correct citations in either one.
					</p>

					<h2>The Short Answer: When to Use APA vs MLA</h2>
					<p>
						<strong>APA (American Psychological Association)</strong> is the standard in the social sciences:
						psychology, sociology, education, nursing, business, and criminology. If your course involves
						research on human behavior, institutions, or data-driven studies, expect APA.
					</p>
					<p>
						<strong>MLA (Modern Language Association)</strong> dominates the humanities: English literature,
						philosophy, history, cultural studies, and foreign languages. MLA is built around analyzing texts,
						so it emphasizes authors and page numbers more prominently than publication dates.
					</p>
					<p>
						Your syllabus or instructor always has the final word. When in doubt, ask — do not assume based
						on your major alone, since interdisciplinary courses sometimes specify a style.
					</p>

					<h2>APA vs MLA at a Glance</h2>
					<p>
						Use this table as a quick reference when switching between formats or double-checking an assignment.
					</p>

					<div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="APA vs MLA comparison table" tabindex="0">
						<table class="compare-table">
							<thead>
								<tr>
									<th scope="col">Feature</th>
									<th scope="col">APA (7th ed.)</th>
									<th scope="col">MLA (9th ed.)</th>
								</tr>
							</thead>
							<tbody>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Primary fields</th>
									<td>Social sciences, education, nursing, business</td>
									<td>Humanities, literature, arts, cultural studies</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Bibliography title</th>
									<td>References</td>
									<td>Works Cited</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">In-text format</th>
									<td>Author–date: (Smith, 2023)</td>
									<td>Author–page: (Smith 42)</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Author name order</th>
									<td>Last name, initials: Smith, J. A.</td>
									<td>Last name, full first name: Smith, John</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Publication date</th>
									<td>Prominent — follows author in references</td>
									<td>At end of entry, after publisher</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Title capitalization</th>
									<td>Sentence case in references</td>
									<td>Title case for books and articles</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Book title formatting</th>
									<td>Italicized</td>
									<td>Italicized</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Article title formatting</th>
									<td>Plain text, sentence case</td>
									<td>Quotation marks, title case</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Website URL</th>
									<td>Full URL, no "Retrieved from"</td>
									<td>Full URL, no http:// if stable</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Title page</th>
									<td>Required (title, author, affiliation, course)</td>
									<td>Not required; name/instructor on first page</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<th scope="row">Running header</th>
									<td>Page number only (student papers)</td>
									<td>Last name + page number</td>
								</tr>
							</tbody>
						</table>
					</div>

					<h2>Key Differences Explained</h2>

					<h3>In-Text Citations: Date vs Page Number</h3>
					<p>
						This is the most visible difference while reading a paper. APA prioritizes <em>when</em> research
						was published because timeliness matters in scientific fields. You write the author's last name
						and the year: (Smith, 2023). Include a page number only for direct quotes: (Smith, 2023, p. 42).
					</p>
					<p>
						MLA prioritizes <em>where</em> in a text an idea appears, since humanities scholars often analyze
						specific passages. You write the author's last name and the page number: (Smith 42). No comma
						between them, and no year in the parentheses unless needed for clarity.
					</p>

					<h3>Reference List vs Works Cited</h3>
					<p>
						APA calls the final bibliography the <strong>References</strong> page. Entries begin with the
						author's last name and initials, followed immediately by the year in parentheses. Everything is
						designed to surface publication dates at a glance.
					</p>
					<p>
						MLA uses <strong>Works Cited</strong>. Entries begin with the author's full last name and first
						name, but the date typically appears near the end. The focus stays on the author and title of the
						work itself rather than when it was published.
					</p>

					<h3>Title and Capitalization Rules</h3>
					<p>
						In APA reference entries, titles use sentence case — only the first word, the first word after a
						colon, and proper nouns are capitalized. In MLA, book and journal titles use title case (major
						words capitalized), while article and web page titles go inside quotation marks.
					</p>
					<p>
						These small formatting choices add up. A journal article title in APA looks like
						<em>Effects of sleep on memory consolidation</em>, while the same title in MLA appears as
						"Effects of Sleep on Memory Consolidation."
					</p>

					<h2>Side-by-Side Citation Examples</h2>
					<p>
						The best way to understand the difference is to cite the same source twice. Below are three common
						source types formatted in both APA 7 and MLA 9.
					</p>

					<h3>Example 1: Book</h3>
					<p class="example-context">Source: A book by John Smith published in 2020 by Penguin Books.</p>
					<p class="format-label">APA 7</p>
					<div class="example-box">
						<p>Smith, J. (2020). <em>The art of academic writing: A practical guide</em>. Penguin Books.</p>
					</div>
					<p class="format-label">MLA 9</p>
					<div class="example-box example-box-mla">
						<p>
							Smith, John. <em>The Art of Academic Writing: A Practical Guide</em>. Penguin Books, 2020.
						</p>
					</div>
					<p class="example-context">
						In-text — APA: (Smith, 2020) · MLA: (Smith 15) <em>with page number for a direct quote</em>
					</p>

					<h3>Example 2: Website</h3>
					<p class="example-context">
						Source: A CDC web page updated March 15, 2024, with no individual author listed.
					</p>
					<p class="format-label">APA 7</p>
					<div class="example-box">
						<p>
							About chronic diseases. (2024, March 15). <em>Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</em>.
							https://www.cdc.gov/chronicdisease/about/index.htm
						</p>
					</div>
					<p class="format-label">MLA 9</p>
					<div class="example-box example-box-mla">
						<p>
							"About Chronic Diseases." <em>Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</em>, 15 Mar. 2024,
							www.cdc.gov/chronicdisease/about/index.htm.
						</p>
					</div>
					<p class="example-context">
						In-text — APA: ("About Chronic Diseases," 2024) · MLA: ("About Chronic Diseases")
					</p>

					<h3>Example 3: Journal Article</h3>
					<p class="example-context">
						Source: A journal article by Maria Garcia in volume 12, issue 3, pages 45–67, published in 2023.
					</p>
					<p class="format-label">APA 7</p>
					<div class="example-box">
						<p>
							Garcia, M. (2023). Neural pathways in adolescent learning. <em>Journal of Educational
							Psychology</em>, <em>12</em>(3), 45–67. https://doi.org/10.1037/example0001234
						</p>
					</div>
					<p class="format-label">MLA 9</p>
					<div class="example-box example-box-mla">
						<p>
							Garcia, Maria. "Neural Pathways in Adolescent Learning." <em>Journal of Educational
							Psychology</em>, vol. 12, no. 3, 2023, pp. 45–67,
							doi:10.1037/example0001234.
						</p>
					</div>
					<p class="example-context">In-text — APA: (Garcia, 2023) · MLA: (Garcia 52)</p>

					<h2>Which One Should You Use?</h2>
					<p>
						Start with your assignment instructions — that overrides every general rule. If the syllabus says
						"APA 7," use APA even in an English class. If no style is specified, consider your field:
					</p>
					<ul>
						<li>
							<strong>Choose APA</strong> for psychology, sociology, anthropology, education, social work,
							nursing, public health, economics, and most STEM-related social research.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong>Choose MLA</strong> for literature, creative writing, film studies, religion,
							philosophy, history, and classical humanities courses.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p>
						Some courses accept either format, but mixing them in a single paper is never acceptable. Pick one
						style and apply it consistently to in-text citations, your bibliography, headings, and margins.
					</p>

					<h2>Common Mistakes When Switching Styles</h2>
					<p>
						Students who learned MLA in high school and encounter APA in college often make predictable errors:
					</p>
					<ul>
						<li>Using page numbers in APA in-text citations for paraphrases (only required for direct quotes)</li>
						<li>Putting article titles in quotation marks in APA (MLA rule, not APA)</li>
						<li>Labeling the final page "Works Cited" in an APA paper (it should say "References")</li>
						<li>Including the year in MLA in-text citations when a page number is available</li>
						<li>Using first-name-only author format from MLA in an APA reference list</li>
					</ul>
					<p>
						Keep a style guide bookmarked for the format you need, or use a citation tool that supports your
						chosen style so you are not rebuilding every entry from memory.
					</p>

					<h2>Final Takeaway</h2>
					<p>
						APA and MLA are not interchangeable — they reflect different academic priorities. APA foregrounds
						dates and research recency; MLA foregrounds authors and textual location. Learn the rules for the
						style your instructor requires, use the comparison table above when you need a refresher, and cite
						consistently throughout your paper. Getting the format right takes practice, but the logic behind
						each system is straightforward once you know which field it serves.
					</p>
				</article>

